                        <bos/>
                        <label.name>ยง</label.name>
                        <label.designator>2:6.</label.designator>
                        <headtext>The Panel&apos;s early decisions</headtext>
                        <eos/>
                        <eop/>
                    </head>
                </doc.title>
            </section.front>
            <section.body>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The Panel&apos;s early decisions provide insight into the Panel&apos;s current operations.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Many of the guidelines followed by the Panel were enunciated in decisions made by the
                        Panel during its first two years of operation.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The decisions entered during this period have been frequently referred to and cited by the
                        Panel more recently.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The early cases provided many disputed issues for resolution by the Panel as litigants
                        attempted to have the Panel&apos;s role defined and delineated.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel&apos;s early decisions reflect the novelty of the issues then decided by it and
                        the importance to the Panel that its decisions reflect the careful consideration of the issues
                        and consideration for the relationship of the Panel to the other courts and judges in the
                        federal judicial system.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I0209c830680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">1</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The creation of the Panel was a progressive step towards improving the management ability
                        of the federal judiciary.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The power to transfer cases for coordinated or consolidated pretrial proceedings is
                        powerful, but the Panel has not wielded the power indiscriminately.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Indeed, the early decisions of the Panel reflect a form of judicial restraint in the
                        exercise of the power to transfer and in the exercise of related powers.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel&apos;s long-standing deference to the transferee judge had its origins in the
                        very earliest decisions it made.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>In <cite.query w-src-number="0304913948" w-serial-number="1969105439" w-seq-number="00001"
                                             w-ref-type="RS" w-pub-number="0000345"
                                             ID="I09ea0982680811e8865b9f61650dcdcd">In re Plumbing
                        </cite.query> Fixtures Case,[<footnote.reference refid="I020b75e0680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">
                            2</footnote.reference>] the Panel transferred multiple cases, including those relating to
                        factually different (although related) claims.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Panel recognized that <?pagebreak label="17"?> this matter could be dealt with by the transferee judge,
                        observing:
                    </paratext>
                    <display.quote>
                        <para>
                            <paratext><begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>The civil actions pending in the Eastern District of
                                Pennsylvania involve alleged conspiracies based upon both indictments in the western
                                District of Pennsylvania, and it therefore seems appropriate to transfer all the cases
                                to the Eastern District of Pennsylvania,
                                <ital>leaving to the transferee judge the solo power to determine in his discretion the
                                    order and procedures for conducting separate pretrial procedures in respect to the
                                    alleged conspiracies.
                                    <eos/>
                                    <bos/>
                                </ital>
                                <end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference
                                        refid="I020b75e1680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">3</footnote.reference>]
                            </paratext>
                        </para>
                    </display.quote>
                    <paratext>The Panel&apos;s deference to the transferee judge undoubtedly a politically prudent
                        course for this new institution and permitted the Panel to avoid controversy that would
                        inevitably follow a more activist approach to the limited authority granted the Panel by
                        statute.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The early cases considered by the Panel presented it with an opportunity for transition.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>Some of the cases had been, before the Panel was created, the subject of proceedings
                        before the Judicial Conference Coordinating Committee and the Panel was permitted to implement
                        decisions consistent with the Coordinating Committee&apos;s vision of the proper role of the
                        Panel and the transferee judge in handling complex litigation.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>In many of the early cases in which transfer was ordered cases were assigned to judges who
                        were members of the Coordinating Committee.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>These judges forged many of the procedures for handling complex and multidistrict
                        litigation that later resulted in the <csc>Manual for Complex Litigation <?pagebreak label="18"?></csc>.[
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>
                        <footnote.reference refid="I020b9cf0680911e88f4a9c1f64101294">4</footnote.reference>]
                    </paratext>
                    <eos/>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
            </section.body>
